      <div class=3D"ym-cbox">
	<h3>The dot product</h3>
      </div>
    </div>
   =20
    <div class=3D"ym-col3">
      <div class=3D"ym-cbox">
=09
	<aside class=3D"box info suggestbackbox">
	  <h4>Suggested background</h4>
	  <ul class=3D"linklist">
	   =20
	    <li><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/vector_introduction" class=3D"c=
ontent" title=3D"An introduction to vectors: A introduction to the concept =
of a vector as an object with magnitude and direction.">An introduction to =
vectors</a></li>
	   =20
	  </ul>
	</aside>
=09
=09
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

      <div class=3D"ym-column linearize-level-1">
        <div id=3D"main_content" class=3D"ym-col1">
          <div class=3D"ym-cbox">
           =20
<p>The dot product between two vectors is based on the projection of one ve=
ctor onto another.=20
Let's imagine we have two vectors $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{b}$, and we want to=20
calculate how much of $\vc{a}$ is pointing in the same direction as the vec=
tor $\vc{b}$.=20
We want a quantity that would be positive if the two vectors are pointing
in similar directions, zero if they are perpendicular, and negative
if the two vectors are pointing in nearly opposite directions.
We will define the dot product between the vectors to capture these quantit=
ies.
</p>

<p>But first, notice that the question =E2=80=9Chow much of $\vc{a}$ is poi=
nting in the same direction as the vector $\vc{b}$=E2=80=9D=20
does not have anything to do with the magnitude (or length) of $\vc{b}$;=20
it is based only on its direction.
(Recall that a vector has <a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/vector_introdu=
ction" class=3D"content" title=3D"An introduction to vectors: A introductio=
n to the concept of a vector as an object with magnitude and direction.">a =
magnitude and a direction</a>.) =20
The answer to this question should not depend on the magnitude of $\vc{b}$,=
 only its direction. =20
To sidestep any confusion caused by the magnitude of $\vc{b}$, let's scale =
the vector so that it has length one.=20
In other words, let's replace $\vc{b}$ with the <a href=3D"https://mathinsi=
ght.org/definition/unit_vector" class=3D"definition" title=3D"Unit vector d=
efinition: A unit vector is a vector of length one.">unit vector</a> that p=
oints in the same direction as $\vc{b}$.
We'll call this vector $\vc{u}$, which is defined by
$$\vc{u} =3D \frac{\vc{b}}{\|\vc{b}\|}.$$</p>

<p>The dot product of $\vc{a}$ with unit vector $\vc{u}$, denoted
$\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u}$, is defined to be the projection of $\vc{a}$ in
the direction of $\vc{u}$, or the amount that $\vc{a}$ is pointing in
the same direction as unit vector $\vc{u}$.
Let's assume for a moment that $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{u}$ are pointing in
similar directions.
Then, you can imagine $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u}$ as the length of the shadow=20
of $\vc{a}$ onto $\vc{u}$ if their tails were together and the
sun was shining from a direction perpendicular to $\vc{u}$.
By forming a right triangle with $\vc{a}$ and this shadow, you
can use geometry to calculate that=20
\begin{gather}\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u} =3D \|\vc{a}\| \cos \theta,
  \label{dot_product_unit}
\end{gather}
where $\theta$ is the angle between $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{u}$.
</p>

<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:dot_product_projection_unit_vecto=
r" class=3D"anchor"></a><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/dot_produc=
t_projection_unit_vector" title=3D"The dot product gives the projection of =
one vector onto a unit vector."><img class=3D"displayed" src=3D"https://mat=
hinsight.org/media/image/image/dot_product_projection_unit_vector.png" alt=
=3D"Dot product as projection onto a unit vector" width=3D"235" height=3D"1=
96"></a></p>

<p>If $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{u}$ were perpendicular, there would be no shadow. =
=20
That corresponds to the case when $\cos \theta =3D \cos \pi/2 =3D0$
and $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u}=3D0$. =20
If the angle $\theta$ between $\vc{a}$ and $\vc{u}$ were larger than $\pi/2=
$,
then the shadow wouldn't hit $\vc{u}$. =20
Since in this case $\cos \theta &lt;0$, the dot product $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u=
}$ is
also negative.=20
You could think of $-\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u}$ (which is positive in this case)
as being the length of the shadow of $\vc{a}$ on the vector $-\vc{u}$,=20
which points in the opposite direction of $\vc{u}$.
</p>

<p>But we need to get back to the dot product $\vc{a}\cdot \vc{b}$, where
$\vc{b}$ may have a magnitude different than one. =20
This dot product $\vc{a}\cdot \vc{b}$ should depend on the magnitude of bot=
h
vectors, $\|\vc{a}\|$ and $\|\vc{b}\|$,=20
and be symmetric in those vectors.=20
Hence, we don't want to define $\vc{a}\cdot \vc{b}$ to be exactly
the projection of $\vc{a}$ on $\vc{b}$;
we want it to reduce to this projection for the case when $\vc{b}$ is a uni=
t vector.
We can accomplish this very easily: just plug the definition $\vc{u}=3D\fra=
c{\vc{b}}{\|\vc{b}\|}$ into our dot product definition of equation \eqref{d=
ot_product_unit}.
This leads to the definition that the dot product $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{b}$,
divided by the magnitude $\|\vc{b}\|$ of $\vc{b}$, is the projection of $\v=
c{a}$ onto $\vc{b}$.
$$\frac{\vc{a}\cdot \vc{b}}{\|\vc{b}\|} =3D \|\vc{a}\| \cos\theta.$$
Then, if we multiply by through by $\|\vc{b}\|$, we get a nice=20
symmetric definition for the dot product $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{b}$.
\begin{gather}
  \vc{a}\cdot \vc{b} =3D \|\vc{a}\| \|\vc{b}\|\cos\theta.
  \label{dot_product_definition}\tag{2}
\end{gather}
</p>


<p>The picture of the geometric interpretation of $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{b}$=20
is almost identical to the above picture for $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{u}$. =20
We just have to remember that we have to divide through by $\|\vc{b}\|$=20
to get the projection of $\vc{a}$ onto $\vc{b}$.</p>

<p class=3D"centeredImage"><a id=3D"image:dot_product_projection" class=3D"=
anchor"></a><a href=3D"https://mathinsight.org/image/dot_product_projection=
" title=3D"The dot product gives the projection of one vector onto another =
vector"><img class=3D"displayed" src=3D"https://mathinsight.org/media/image=
/image/dot_product_projection.png" alt=3D"Dot product as projection of vect=
ors" width=3D"306" height=3D"215"></a></p>

<p>In the following interactive applet, you can explore this
geometric intrepretation of the dot product, and observe how it depends=20
on the vectors and the angle between them.  (The reported number shouldn't
depend on the length of $\|\vc{b}\|$ since we divided by that magnitude.)</=
p>

<a id=3D"applet:dot_product_projection" class=3D"anchor"></a><section class=
=3D"appletbox"><div class=3D"javascriptapplet"><div class=3D"geogebrawebapp=
let" id=3D"containerAppletDotProductProjection01" style=3D"min-width:550px;=
min-height:397px"></div></div>
<p><i>The dot product as projection.</i> The dot product of the vectors $\v=
c{a}$ (in blue) and $\vc{b}$ (in green), when divided by the magnitude of $=
\vc{b}$, is the projection of $\vc{a}$ onto $\vc{b}$.  This projection is i=
llustrated by the red line segment from the tail of $\vc{b}$ to the project=
ion of the head of $\vc{a}$ on $\vc{b}$.  You can change the vectors $\vc{a=
}$ and $\vc{b}$ by dragging the points at their ends or dragging the vector=
s themselves.  Notice how the dot product is positive for acute angles and =
negative for obtuse angles.  The reported number does not depend on $\|\vc{=
b}\|$ only because we've divided through by that magnitude.</p><p><a href=
=3D"https://mathinsight.org/applet/dot_product_projection" title=3D"The dot=
 product of two vectors is illustrated as a projection from one vector to t=
he other." class=3D"applet">More information about applet.</a> </p></sectio=
n>


<p>The geometric definition of equation \eqref{dot_product_definition} make=
s the properties of the dot product clear. =20
One can see immediately from the formula that the dot product $\vc{a}\cdot\=
vc{b}$ is positive for acute angles and negative for obtuse angles.
The formula demonstrates that the dot product grows linearly with the lengt=
h of both vectors and is commutative, i.e., $\vc{a} \cdot \vc{b} =3D \vc{b}=
 \cdot \vc{a}$.</p>

<p>However, the geometric formula \eqref{dot_product_definition} is not con=
venient for calculating the dot product when we are given the vectors $\vc{=
a}$ and $\vc{b}$ in terms of their components.
To facilitate such calculations, we derive a <a href=3D"https://mathinsight=
.org/dot_product_formula_components" class=3D"content" title=3D"The formula=
 for the dot product in terms of vector components: Derivation of the compo=
nent formula for the dot product, starting with its geometric definition ba=
sed on projection of vectors.">formula for the dot product</a> in terms of =
vector components.
With such formula in hand, we can run through <a href=3D"https://mathinsigh=
t.org/dot_product_examples" class=3D"content" title=3D"Dot product examples=
: Examples of calculating the dot product of two- and three-dimensional vec=
tors.">examples of calculating the dot product</a>.

          </p></div>
        </div>
